05784nam a22008775i 9780231548175DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20192019nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2018033079  a97802315481757 a10.7312/john189102doi  a(DE-B1597)517748  a(OCoLC)1048659018  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aHQ76.3.U5bJ583 2019 7aBUS0770002bisacsh1 aJohnson, David K., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBuying Gay :bHow Physique Entrepreneurs Sparked a Movement /cDavid K. Johnson. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource :b55 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aColumbia Studies in the History of U.S. Capitalism00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction -- t1. Emerging from the Muscle Magazines: Bob Mizer’s Athletic Model Guild -- t2. Selling Gay Books: Donald Webster Cory’s “Business with a Conscience” -- t3. The Grecian Guild: Imagining a Gay Past, and Future -- t4. “I Want a Pen Pal!”: Postmaster General Arthur Summerfield and the Adonis Male Club -- t5. Defending a Naked Boy: Lynn Womack at the Supreme Court -- t6. Consolidating the Market: DSI of Minneapolis -- t7. The Physique Legacy -- tAcknowledgments -- tAbbreviations -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1951, a new type of publication appeared on newsstands—the physique magazine produced by and for gay men. For many men growing up in the 1950s and 1960s, these magazines and their images and illustrations of nearly naked men, as well as articles, letters from readers, and advertisements, served as an initiation into gay culture. The publishers behind them were part of a wider world of “physique entrepreneurs”: men as well as women who ran photography studios, mail-order catalogs, pen-pal services, book clubs, and niche advertising for gay audiences. Such businesses have often been seen as peripheral to the gay political movement. In this book, David K. Johnson shows how gay commerce was not a byproduct but rather an important catalyst for the gay rights movement.Offering a vivid look into the lives of physique entrepreneurs and their customers, and presenting a wealth of illustrations, Buying Gay explores the connections—and tensions—between the market and the movement. With circulation rates many times higher than the openly political “homophile” magazines, physique magazines were the largest gay media outlets of their time. This network of producers and consumers helped foster a gay community and upend censorship laws, paving the way for open expression. Physique entrepreneurs were at the center of legal struggles, especially against the U.S. Post Office, including the court victory that allowed full-frontal male nudity and open homoeroticism. Buying Gay reconceives the history of the gay rights movement and shows how consumer culture helped create community and a site for resistance.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aBodybuildingxPeriodicalszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aBodybuildingzUnited StatesxPeriodicalsxHistory. 0aGay business enterpriseszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aGay consumerszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aGay eroticazUnited StatesxHistory. 0aGay menzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aGay rightszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Corporate & Business History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065195908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08i